docs/TECH_STACK.md:
# Tech Stack

Recommended technologies for the agentic task manager (control plane, workers, CLI, Web UI). Alternatives are noted where relevant.

---

## 1. Control Plane (Server) — Rust

| Layer | Recommendation | Rationale | Alternatives |
|-------|----------------|-----------|--------------|
| **Language / Runtime** | **Rust** | Single binary, no runtime; same language as workers and CLI for shared types and one toolchain. Strong concurrency (tokio), great for HTTP + **SSE** streaming (log tail, session events). | Go, Python (FastAPI) |
| **API** | **REST + SSE (v1)** | REST for CRUD and worker polling; **Server-Sent Events** for log tail and session events. WebSocket is **not** part of the v1 real-time contract. | gRPC + streaming for more rigid RPC |
| **Registry / State DB** | **PostgreSQL** or **SQLite** (dev) | Sessions, workers, jobs, inbox metadata, config. PostgreSQL for production scale. | SQLite for single-node / dev only |
| **Task queue / dispatch** | **PostgreSQL table** | Task queue lives in a Postgres table (same DB as registry/sessions). Workers get tasks by **polling** the API. No Redis, NATS, or DB LISTEN/NOTIFY in v1. | — |
| **Log storage** | **v1: Dual-write.** (1) Local files on each component (control plane + workers), with rotation (size or time; implementation-defined). (2) Central store = **PostgreSQL** on the control plane for all logs that reach it. | — |

**Rust control-plane crates (suggested):** `axum` (HTTP + SSE), `tokio`, `sqlx` (PostgreSQL), `serde` / `serde_json`, `tracing`, `tower` (middleware).

## 2. Workers (Rust)

| Layer | Recommendation | Rationale | Alternatives |
|-------|----------------|-----------|--------------|
| **Language** | **Rust** | Single binary, no runtime; great for long-running workers and resource control. | Go, Python |
| **Agent runtime** | **Claude Code or Cursor CLI** (BYOL) | v1 supports these two CLIs only. | — |
| **Git** | **`git2`** (libgit2 bindings) | Clone, checkout, commit, push from worker. | Shell-out to `git` CLI |
| **Execution isolation** | **Process per task** (or container later) | One clone + one agent run per process; clear cleanup. | Containers |

## 3. CLI — Rust

| Layer | Recommendation | Rationale | Alternatives |
|-------|----------------|-----------|--------------|
| **Language** | **Rust** (`clap`) | One binary, easy to ship; shares types and API client code | Go, Python |
| **Config** | **Env vars + config file** | `CONTROL_PLANE_URL`, `API_KEY`; optional profile per environment. | Env only |
| **Real-time** | **SSE** for `logs tail` and `attach` | Same endpoints as Web UI. | Long-polling |

## 4. Web UI

| Layer | Recommendation | Rationale | Alternatives |
|-------|----------------|-----------|--------------|
| **Stack** | **React** (or **Vite + React**) + **TypeScript** | Component model fits dashboards; TypeScript for API types. | Vue, Svelte |
| **State / data** | **TanStack Query (React Query)** + **SSE** for live data | REST for sessions, workers, jobs; **SSE** for log tail and session events. | SWR, Redux + thunk |
| **UI components** | **Tailwind CSS** + **shadcn/ui** or **Radix** | Fast, accessible, good DX. | MUI, Chakra, custom |
| **Real-time** | **SSE** for log stream and session updates | Same as CLI. v1: SSE only for tail/attach. | Polling (fallback) |

## 7. Repo Layout (Rust Monorepo)

```
remote_harness/
├── crates/
│   ├── server/
│   ├── worker/
│   ├── cli/
│   └── api-types/
├── web/
│   ├── src/
│   └── package.json
├── docs/
├── Cargo.toml
├── Cargo.lock
├── Dockerfile
├── docker-compose.yml
└── README.md
```

docs/CLIENT_EXPERIENCE.md:
# Client experience (CLI & Web UI)

## 1. Principles
| Principle | Meaning |
|-----------|---------|
| **Same truth everywhere** | CLI and Web UI surface the same session/job state and errors from the API. |
| **Fail loud, classify** | On failure, show a **clear message**, the server **`error.code`** when present, and whether the user can fix it. |
| **Streaming resilience** | Log and session **SSE** streams disconnect; clients **reconnect with backoff**. |
| **No silent CORS or network** | Distinguish **network / CORS / DNS** from **401** from **5xx**. |

## 2. API errors (REST)
### 2.1 Web UI mapping
| Situation | What to show | Action hints |
|-----------|----------------|--------------|
| **`401`** | "Not authorized" + server `message` | Check Settings → API key |
| **`400`** | Server `message` + field hints | Fix form input |
| **`404`** | Resource missing | Link back to list view |
| **`409`** | e.g. session not accepting input | Explain state; suggest refresh |
| **`500`** | "Something went wrong on the server" | Retry |
| **`503` on OAuth start** | "Sign-in is not configured on this server" | Admin must set OAuth env vars |

## 5. Credentials and BYOL
| Situation | UX |
|-----------|-----|
| **Session create rejected** (missing git or agent token) | Direct user to Settings → Credentials |
| **Token health** | Use auth-status for Git expiry messaging |

## 8. Git commit, push, and PR/MR outcomes
### 8.1 Mapping API state to user-visible copy
| Situation | Web UI / CLI requirement |
|-----------|---------------------------|
| **Job failed** (`failed`, `error_message` set) | Show error_message prominently; link to Settings → Credentials when auth-related |
| **Job completed, no `commit_ref`** | Explain that push/commit did not complete; point to logs |
| **Job completed with commit, no `pull_request_url`** when PR mode | Show one-line reason: job not successful; missing branch/title; provider not GitHub/GitLab; provider API error |
| **Agent exited non-zero but commits may exist** | Explain job status reflects agent exit, Git may still show commits |

### 8.2 Operator signals (logs)
| Data from API | UI / CLI behavior |
|---------------|-------------------|
| `jobs[].error_message` | Always visible on job row when set; never hide behind "Failed" alone |
| `jobs[].status` + `pull_request_url` | If expected MR missing after completion, show explanation per §8.1 |
| `commit_ref` / branch fields | If missing when push expected, point to logs |

## 12. Long chat sessions
When `task_input.history_truncated` is `true`, show that only the latest N turns are sent.

